0.body: GreenFlow is a comprehensive toolkit designed to facilitate experiments measuring energy consumption in distributed cloud settings. Typically run in data center environments, it leverages a cloud-native workflow using Kubernetes, enabling precise measurement and attribution of power consumption to specific processes and nodes through the Scaphandre toolkit.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: GreenFlow consists of several key components working together to provide a robust experimental framework: Core Python Package : Contains the main logic for orchestration, state handling, and experiment storage. For more details, see Key Components . Entrypoint : The entrypoint.py file serves as the main entry point for running experiments. It handles command-line interactions and imports necessary modules. Learn more in Using the Entrypoint . Configuration Management : Utilizes the Gin library for dependency injection and configuration management. For details, refer to Configuration with Gin . Prometheus Integration : Used for monitoring and data collection, with support for remote write capability. See Prometheus Setup for more information. For a complete overview of the system architecture, see System Overview .
1.title: System Overview

10.body: Setting up the GreenFlow project locally is streamlined thanks to the use of Nix for dependency management and environment configuration. This approach ensures consistency across different development environments and simplifies the setup process.
10.breadcrumbs: Setting Up GreenFlow » Requirements » Local Project Setup
10.title: Local Project Setup

11.body: Before you begin, ensure you have the following installed on your system: Nix : We use the Determinate Systems Nix installer for a consistent setup. direnv (optional, recommended): This tool automatically loads and unloads environment variables based on the current directory.
11.title: Prerequisites

12.body:
Install Nix (if not already installed): Use the Determinate Systems Nix installer by running the following command in your terminal: curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf -L https://install.determinate.systems/nix | sh -s -- install Install direnv : Installation methods may vary depending on your operating system. For most Unix-like systems, you can use your package manager. For example: ▪	On macOS with Homebrew: brew install direnv ▪	On Ubuntu or Debian: sudo apt-get install direnv For other systems, refer to the direnv installation guide. Clone the GreenFlow repository: git clone https://github.com/autolyticus/greenflow.git
cd greenflow Set up direnv: direnv allow This command should automatically download and set up all required dependencies, including Ansible, Python, and any other project-specific tools. Verifying the Setup After running nix develop, your environment should be ready for GreenFlow development. You can verify the setup by running: python --version ansible --version These commands should display the versions of Python and Ansible specified in the project's Nix configuration. Automatic Environment Activation With direnv properly set up, the Nix environment will automatically activate when you enter the project directory and deactivate when you leave it. This ensures that you're always using the correct versions of tools and dependencies for the GreenFlow project. Troubleshooting If you encounter any issues during the setup process: 1.	Ensure that Nix and direnv are correctly installed and configured. 2.	Check that your .envrc file is properly set up and allowed by direnv. 3.	If changes are made to the Nix configuration, you may need to run nix develop again to update the environment. For more detailed troubleshooting, refer to the Troubleshooting section of this documentation.

2.body: GreenFlow leverages Scaphandre for detailed energy breakdowns. Key points to note: Relies on Intel RAPL (Running Average Power Limit) technology. Requires a recent Linux kernel with PowerCap interface enabled. Needs bare-metal access to the cluster for CPU register access. Measures energy consumption for CPU and RAM, but not peripherals, storage, or cooling systems. For more on energy measurement, see Scaphandre and Energy Measurement .
2.title: Energy Measurement with Scaphandre

3.body: GreenFlow's workflow, initially designed for the Grid'5000 testbed, involves: Provisioning : Deploying a Kubernetes cluster using K3S. Infrastructure Deployment : Setting up Scaphandre, Prometheus, and other necessary services. Experiment Execution : Running one or more experiments within a deployment. Data Collection and Analysis : Collecting and analyzing experiment results. For a detailed explanation of the workflow, refer to Workflow Overview .
3.title: Workflow Overview

4.body: To begin using GreenFlow: Review the Requirements for running GreenFlow. Follow the Configuration with Gin guide to set up your environment. Learn how to design and run experiments in Running Experiments . Understand how to analyze your results in Data Collection and Analysis . For troubleshooting and common questions, refer to the Troubleshooting section and Appendix: FAQ . By following this documentation, you'll be able to run reproducible experiments to measure and analyze energy consumption in distributed systems using GreenFlow.
4.title: Getting Started
